# Local OIDC Test Provider (Keycloak-compatible mindset)

## Preferred Stack
- Use Node.js + TypeScript.
- Framework: Fastify (HTTP API) + openid-provider (OIDC server).
- JWT signing: jose.
- UI: simple server-rendered pages (Nunjucks/Handlebars) or minimal React/Vite.

## Why Node.js here
- `openid-provider` is mature and purpose-built for OIDC/OAuth2 flows.
- Faster setup for a lightweight local identity emulator.
- Easy JWT/JWKS handling and standard OIDC discovery endpoints.

## Functional Requirements
- Must run locally as a lightweight OIDC provider for Web API testing.
- Test users are defined in config and do not require TOTP.
- Provide a simple web UI to "act as user" and issue tokens quickly.
- Expose standard OIDC endpoints:
  - `/.well-known/openid-configuration`
  - `/protocol/openid-connect/auth`
  - `/protocol/openid-connect/token`
  - `/protocol/openid-connect/certs` (JWKS)
- Issue signed JWT access tokens (and optionally ID tokens) with role claims.

## Claims and Token Conventions
- Keep claims compatible with existing backend authorization checks.
- Include standard claims: `iss`, `aud`, `sub`, `exp`, `iat`, `scope`.
- Include role claims in Keycloak-like shape when needed:
  - `realm_access.roles`
  - `resource_access.{clientId}.roles`
- Support configurable issuer, audience, client IDs, scopes, token lifetime.

## Configuration Rules
- Store test identities in a single config file (`users.yaml` or `users.json`).
- Each user entry should define:
  - `username`
  - `sub`
  - `email` (optional)
  - `roles` (realm and/or client roles)
  - `scopes`
- Never hardcode users in application code.

## UI Rules
- Provide a minimal "Login as" page listing test users.
- One-click user selection should establish session and allow token issuance.
- Show issued token and decoded claims for easy API testing.

## Security and Boundaries
- Local/dev use only; do not deploy as production identity provider.
- Keep private signing keys in local-only storage (env/file), never committed.
- Default bind address should be localhost.

## Implementation Guidance
- Prefer simple, explicit code over heavy abstractions.
- Add integration tests for discovery, token issuance, and claim shape.
- Keep startup with a single command (`npm run dev` / `docker compose up`).
